ifically at src/test/resources/org/jline/nativ/Windows/x86_64/jlinenative.dll. I wonder if that would take precedence over the jar's resources, especially given the loading order with Class.getResourceAsStream. In a Gradle test runtime, test resources are usually prioritized. I need a valid ELF shared object to move forward, and it seems like compiling a small shared object might be more efficient than adding a larger existing library.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring OS compatibility**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out how setting the os.name to Windows/x86_64 might enforce the use of the ELF. However, I know that on non-Linux systems like macOS, using System.load on an ELF will fail. I wonder if I can handle this gracefully in my reports since Linux is likely the main focus. Perhaps instead of storing resources, I could use an existing JDK library at runtime. Yet, that resource needs to exist before I can call getResourceAsStream, which complicates things.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating native-image support**\\n\\nI'm looking into whether loading arbitrary valid .so files into a native-image executable via System.load is supported. It seems like System.load should work at runtime for dynamic libraries, but I'm not entirely sure about the native image supporting this for JNI. I think it might require enabling native access. I've noticed that jline has native-image.properties, so I need to inspect that further to gather more insight.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_mkH6URKpzbdOBsnt9qGOn9wV|fc_0b729fb16c69f5be0169f924668780819084e73665ec6a81a8", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "jar xf /home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.aesh/readline/3.0/cb2b1e859c3ed74aa068ced7bbaec2185bd5ec40/readline-3.0.jar META-INF/native-image/org.jline/jline-native/native-image.properties && cat META-INF/native-image/org.jline/jline-native/native-image.properties; rm -rf META-INF"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "prov